<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910712-0126</DOCNO><DOCID>910712-0126.</DOCID><HL>   EPA Seeks Penalties   Exceeding $6 Million   From Chemical Firms</HL><DATE>07/12/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5</SO><CO>   G.BAY U.ACO</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)</MS><IN>CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)ENVIRONMENT (ENV)</IN><NS>ENVIRONMENTAL NEWS (ENV)</NS><GV>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)</GV><RE>EUROPE (EU)GERMANY (GE)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)VIRGINIA (VA)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   PHILADELPHIA -- The federal Environmental ProtectionAgency said it is seeking penalties in excess of $6 millionfrom two chemical companies for alleged violations of theToxic Substances Control Act.   The EPA is seeking penalties totaling more than $4.7million against Mobay Corp., a Pittsburgh-based unit ofGermany's Bayer AG. The EPA alleges that Mobay importedchemical substances for commercial use which were not on theEPA's inventory of certified chemicals, falsely certifiedthat import shipments were in compliance with the act,provided false information to the EPA regarding the datesthat certain substances were first imported and otherviolations.</LP><TEXT>   An official at Mobay said the company believes it hascomplied with the regulations, and will reply to the EPAcomplaint within 20 days.   In a separate action, the EPA is seeking more than $2million in penalties from Allied Colloids Inc., Suffolk, Va.The EPA alleges that Allied imported and distributed sevennew chemical substances, but failed to gain proper and timelycertification for the imports.   An official at Allied said the company planned to &quot;pursueall available options&quot; regarding the penalty assessments.   For its part, the EPA said it hopes the large penaltiesfor the violations will send a message to other chemicalcompanies to obey the law.</TEXT></DOC>